<!-- SYSTEM DESIGN CASE STUDY -->
<section id="systemdesign">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-label">Deep Dive</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">How the Flash Sale Engine <span style="color:var(--accent)">actually works</span></h2>
    <p class="section-sub">Most portfolios list what a project does. This is how I reasoned through it — the problem, the decisions, and what I'd change at 100x scale.</p>
    <div class="section-divider"></div>
 
    <div class="case-study">
      <div class="case-header">
        <span class="case-badge">Concurrency &amp; Correctness</span>
        <span class="case-title">Preventing overselling under concurrent writes</span>
      </div>
 
      <div class="case-grid">
        <div class="case-block">
          <h4>The Problem</h4>
          <p>When 50 buyers hit "Buy" on the same 10-unit product within milliseconds of each other, a naive <code>read stock → check &gt; 0 → decrement</code> flow has a race condition: two requests can both read stock as 1, both pass the check, and both decrement — overselling the item.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="case-block">
          <h4>The Approach</h4>
          <p>Replaced the read-then-write pattern with a single atomic MongoDB operation: <code>findOneAndUpdate</code> with a query condition (<code>stock: {"{"} $gt: 0 {"}"}</code>) and decrement in the same call. The database — not application code — guarantees only one request can win each unit of stock.</p>
          <p>Added Redis-based rate limiting in front of the checkout endpoint to absorb request bursts before they hit the database, and WebSocket broadcasts so all connected clients see stock counts update in real time without polling.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="case-block">
          <h4>Verifying It</h4>
          <p>Stress-tested with 50 concurrent buyer requests against a 10-unit stock pool. Result: exactly 10 successful purchases, 40 clean rejections, zero overselling across repeated runs — confirming the atomic operation holds under real concurrent load, not just in theory.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
 
      <div class="case-block" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
        <h4>Trade-offs Considered</h4>
        <table class="tradeoff-table">
          <tr><th>Approach</th><th>Why not used here</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Application-level locking (mutex/semaphore)</td><td>Works in a single process, but breaks the moment the app scales to multiple instances — locks don't cross servers</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Pessimistic DB row locking</td><td>Correct, but serializes requests and hurts throughput under high concurrency compared to an atomic conditional update</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Optimistic locking with retries</td><td>Viable alternative; atomic <code>findOneAndUpdate</code> was chosen for lower latency since it resolves in one round trip instead of read-write-retry cycles</td></tr>
        </table>
      </div>
 
      <div class="case-block" style="margin-top:1.5rem">
        <h4>What I'd Change at 100x Scale</h4>
        <p>Move the stock counter into Redis (single-threaded, in-memory, atomic <code>DECR</code>) as the source of truth for the hot path, with MongoDB updated asynchronously for persistence — trading a small window of eventual consistency for much higher throughput than a single database can sustain under extreme concurrent load.</p>
        <p>This project intentionally stayed at the "one strongly-consistent database" scale to reason through it fully rather than jump straight to a distributed design I hadn't verified myself.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

